posts.subject: Ddl Zan Mussolini
posts.body:
"Il fascismo femminile che porta bravamente la gloriosa camicia nera e si raccoglie intorno ai nostri gagliardetti, è destinato a scrivere una storia splendida, a lasciare tracce memorabili, a dare un contributo sempre più profondo di passioni e di opere al fascismo italiano." (da Scritti e discorsi, vol. III, p. 109)

Libertà di pensiero, di parola e di stampa? Sì, purché regolata e moderata da limiti giusti, chiaramente stabiliti. Senza di che, si avrebbe anarchia e licenza. E ricordatevi, sopra tutto la morale deve avere i suoi diritti. (da Testamento politico di Mussolini: Dettato, corretto, siglato da lui il 22 aprile 1945, a cura di Gian Gaetano Cabella, Arti Grafiche Pedanesi, 1972)

posts.subject: M51 big image test
posts.body:
Big file tested with the new hardware! (the image used is the same used for the logo of this zite). 

M51 galaxy from Hubble Space Telescope ("fullsize original" version used): https://esahubble.org/images/heic0506a/

Methods:
Software used: LifeX to create GLCM indicators whole image maps for the RGB components of the image separated by using GIMP.
gray range: 0-256
number of gray levels: 64
kernel diamater: 7 pixels

I'm not an expert in astronomy, but i see more homogenity around galactic nuclei than external arms. Also some stars appears bright by using disorder indicators like GLCM entropy while others appears bright by using GLCM energy.

posts.subject: Pluto images from New Horizon spaceprobe (original ones)
posts.body:
I found the original Pluto and Charon photos taken by the LORRI instrument of the New Horizon spaceprobe and tried to elaborate them with LifeX.

original database: https://pds-smallbodies.astro.umd.edu/holdings/nh-p-lorri-2-pluto-v3.0/dataset.shtml

Objectives:
1)veriy if the results previously obtained by using the same pics in .jpg file format are equal to the same obtained by using the original pics in FITS file format (converted to TIFF file format to be read by LifeX ,preserving the original grayscale by using Avis FITS viewer)

2)verify if more near-object images give results compatible with more distant images (indicator are objective measures indipendent from zooming?)

3)create a database for astronomers (test "local texture map as a service")

methods:

software used:
AVIS FITS viewer to convert fits images to tiff file format
LifeX software to create whole image texture maps of five GLCM indicators (dissimilarity, entropy, contrast, energy and homogeneity)
the .zip structure included in this post use folder names to include map files and screenshots of the FITS files referred by the parent folder name.

Parameters used by LifeX:

number of gray levels: 64
range: 0-max
kernel diameter: 7 pixels

Results:
1)by using original FITS/TIFF files i obtained the same maps by using JPG files taken from another source in a previous experiment already reported in this zite

2)"zoomed" images give similar results to global ones

3)i can render New Horizon maps in seconds, big file render of M51 pic give results in around 30 minutes per RGB component. 

Conclusions:

1) rescaled JPG pics give the same result of original FITS/TIFF grayscaled images. Because of this we probably can use rescaled images or also normal pics to obtain the same results taken from original media (the previous study that i conducted by using JPG pics of COVID-19 TC patients probably gave the same results of a DICOM based one rescaled with the lung window range)

2) imaging zoom don't alter the results obtained from the maps

3) a powerful hardware can be used to help other people to create big databases for study or artistic purposes (i like many fused pics of Pluto! :)
